Well, lemme tell ya, I'm gonna be a social worker, helpin' out them poor kids who got mistreated, ya know? And I'll be workin' with families who are havin' a hard time.  I reckon I got a few things to offer this social work gig, like bein' helpful, treatin' folks right, doin' things the right way, and tryin' to make things better between people. And I'm talkin' 'bout makin' myself better too, so I can do my job real good.

Truth be told, I always wanted to help folks out, but I wasn't sure how.  In high school and college, I saw folks runnin' from their problems, avoidin' 'em like the plague. Some tried to cope, but not real good, if ya catch my drift. I even got a degree in psychology from Piedmont College back in '09, just tryin' to figure things out.

Then one summer, I met this sixteen-year-old kid, nervous as a cat in a room full of rocking chairs. My friend told me he was runnin' from his abusive parents. The next day, I found out he called the cops on 'em. So, I figured I'd see what I could do, so I went over to their house. I talked to the cops, told 'em I was a psychology grad from Piedmont. They asked me to talk to the parents 'cause there wasn't much they could do for the kid. When I questioned 'em, they were all jumpy and makin' excuses about their son bein' manipulative for gettin' the cops involved. That's when I knew, I gotta be a social worker, helpin' kids caught in these family messes.

Another thing that's important to me is social justice.  We say we value each person, but sometimes it feels like we just want everyone to be the same. I'm me, and I ain't afraid to be different.  Back in school, I protested against injustice whenever I could.  Colored my hair crazy colors, wore what I wanted, pierced my ears, joined that GSBA group, stood up against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice, and I'll keep fightin' for it.

Alright, so this here paper's gonna talk about two ways of lookin' at insomnia - the "sciencey" way and the "people and their surroundings" way.

The sciencey way, they call it the biological model, focuses on stuff like your genes and your overall health. It's all about how your body's wired to sleep and what happens when things go wrong. 

Then there's the "people and their surroundings" way, which is called the sociocultural model. This one looks at how your environment, your family, your neighborhood, and even your job can affect your sleep. 

This paper's gonna go through both these models and talk about some studies that tried to figure out how they work.  We'll also talk about the good and bad parts of each study, ya know, like what they got right and where they might have missed the mark.

Now, sleep problems can come in all shapes and sizes. Sometimes they're just about sleep itself - like trouble falling asleep or staying asleep. Other times, they're connected to other stuff going on in your head, like stress or anxiety. And sometimes they're caused by medical conditions or things you're taking.

The paper's gonna focus mainly on insomnia, which is that trouble falling asleep or staying asleep. It'll also touch on other sleep problems that are similar.

One study looked at something called the GABAB receptor. Turns out, this little fella in your brain is important for sleep.  They did some experiments on mice, and found that messing with this receptor can mess with their sleep.  It's kinda like a light switch for sleep. 

So what does this mean for us humans? Well, it means that our genes might play a role in how well we sleep. And if something's wrong with that GABAB receptor, it could make it harder to get a good night's rest.

Alright, so listen up, 'cause I'm gonna tell ya about this thing called CAPD. It's basically when your brain, the big boss, can't quite figure out what it's hearing. Think of it like this: you can hear perfectly fine, but your brain's like, "Huh? What was that?" 

Now, back in the day, folks called it "auditory imperception," like it was some kinda secret code. But these smart folks started figuring out that it wasn't just kids not paying attention, it was their brains messing up the sound signals. They started doing tests to see how people's brains handled sounds, like trying to tell apart two words said at the same time. 

So, what happens when someone's got CAPD? Well, they might have a hard time telling where a sound is coming from, or they might mix up similar sounds. It's like trying to follow a conversation when there's a lot of noise around. They might even miss cues in someone's voice, like sarcasm or jokes. 

Now, how do you know if someone's got CAPD? Well, you gotta watch how they listen and do some tests. It's kind of like a detective trying to solve a mystery. They'll ask questions, play sounds, and see how the person reacts. There ain't no magic bullet test, but they'll look for patterns and clues.

So this play, Twelfth Night, it's sayin' somethin' about pretendin'. See, it can work for a while, keepin' up a fake face, but eventually, you gotta drop the act.  Otherwise, you might just lose yourself, ya know? The problem is, when you do let the truth out, things can get messy.  Folks might get mad, feel betrayed. It's a tough choice, like pickin' between yourself and your friends. Some folks might not care if you've been tellin' fibs, but others, well, they get their feelings hurt easy.

Now, this whole pretendin' thing gets even trickier when it comes to switchin' up your gender. Why'd ya wanna pretend to be someone you ain't? 

Take Viola, for example. She's gotta put on a guy's clothes to stay safe in a foreign land.  It's a way to protect herself, see? But guess what? It pushes her away from other women, the folks she coulda relied on.  And then things get even weirder when Olivia, this woman, falls head over heels for her, thinkin' she's a dude!  And don't forget, Viola's got feelings for Orsino, but she can't let on, 'cause she's playin' the part.  It's a tangled web!

This play, it kinda shows how fakin' it can bring out hidden stuff, like feelings you ain't even aware of.  Maybe Olivia's drawn to Viola 'cause she's disguised as a man, or maybe, just maybe, Olivia's got some feelings for women she's keepin' under wraps.  

But here's the thing, this Olivia, she's probably just makin' fun of folks who judge others by their looks.  She switches her affections from Viola to Sebastian real quick, like it's nothin'.  She even starts seein' Viola as family, not a lover.  So maybe it ain't so much about hidden feelings, but more about pointin' out how folks can be shallow.

Alman, y'all know how the Germans were real meanies back in the day, especially to them folks in South West Africa. They went and did some real messed up stuff there, like wiping out whole groups of people. But you gotta remember, not every part of the German empire was like that. Some places were good, some were bad, just like everywhere else. 

Now, when it came to schoolin' folks, it was the same way. Some places, like East Africa, the Germans built schools and taught the local folks to read and write.  People back then even said how great the Germans were doin' with education in places like Kamerun. 

But down in South West Africa, things were different. They didn't have much interest in teachin' the local people. Mostly, it was left up to the churches to do that, and they didn't get much help from the government. The Germans, though, they were all about schoolin' their own folks. They built schools for them and helped the churches run their schools too.

This messed things up for South West Africa for a long time, even after the Germans left. While other places had lots of folks who could read and write, in South West Africa, most people couldn't even read a lick. 

There are lots of books written about how the Germans ran their colonies, mostly back when they were still in charge.  Some folks even compared how things worked in different places, like East Africa and South West Africa. They found that the Germans treated folks differently in each place, and that's what this paper wants to talk about.

Listen,  music's changed a whole bunch in the last hundred years. There's so many dang types now, like rock, country, rap, jazz, and even folk.  And each of those has got a bunch of little types too, like little pups in a litter. Heavy metal's one of those that really went wild, man. It's like a big ol' family reunion, but instead of cousins, you got  sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, all rippin' and roarin'. 

It's got all these different emotions, mostly the dark ones, like anger, sadness, and a whole lotta angst. But it's also really good at showin' off how talented these musicians are. 

It's hard to say what metal even is anymore, 'cause it's borrowed from so many other things. But we gotta go back to the start, y'know? To see where this whole thing came from. Metal ain't just some genre, it's a whole movement, like a wildfire sweepin' through the music world. 

Metal's all about bein' loud, man. More bass, more volume, more everything! It's raw, it's real, and it's not afraid to get dark. Back in the 70s, folks were takin' a lot of drugs, and that messed with their heads in a good way. They started makin' music that sounded like it came from another planet. It was heavy, it was weird, and it was different.  

Metal's got this darkness to it, somethin' that wasn't really around much in popular music before. Like, even the Beatles got in on it - that song "Helter Skelter" is pretty darn dark. It was like they were tryin' to prove they could be just as heavy as the Rolling Stones.  That's the heart of metal, man. It's about bein' raw, bein' real, and not shyin' away from the darkness.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout this fella, Henri Rousseau. Before them fancy Surrealists got all weird with their paintin', this guy was dreamin' up his own kinda dreams, you know?  He was a Post-Impressionist, real good, did a picture called "The Dream" way back in 1910. It ain't just some lady lookin' at pretty stuff in her sleep, it's Rousseau pourin' his heart and soul into it. He wanted everyone to like his art, ya know, the critics, the fancy folks. But he was stuck in a pickle.  Should he paint like everyone else to get ahead, or just be himself and hope for the best? That's what this "Dream" picture is all about, his big ol' struggle. 

Now, this Rousseau fella, he wasn't born with a silver spoon, that's for sure.  Grew up in France, his daddy sold stuff, but nothing fancy.  Never went to art school, worked for the government collectin' tolls, even got called a customs inspector though he wasn't. Lost his wife and kids, poor fella, so he picked up a paintbrush to escape his troubles. He wanted to paint like the common folk, tell their stories, ya know?  But the art world was tough, full of fancy artists who knew all the tricks.  He was older than most, and trying to catch up.

He wanted to be one of the big shots, just like Matisse, another famous painter, but they were different. Matisse was all about bein' unique,  Rousseau just wanted to fit in, paint what everyone expected and get accepted.

Dang, folks, ya know how some smart guys say bein' good and lookin' pretty is like twins?  I reckon they're right.  Like that fella Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That's all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn a lot from schoolin' and livin', but knowin' right from wrong and what's beautiful, well, that just kinda hits ya. 

See, we ain't taught how to appreciate art or good deeds, we just know it when we see it.  It's like tryin' to explain what makes a good song - you can talk about the chords and rhythm, but that ain't the whole story.  It's somethin' more, somethin' you feel deep down.

Now, take that fancy Mona Lisa everyone's always goin' on about. You can talk about the paintin' all day long, but it's that somethin' else, that je ne sais quoi, that makes it tick. 

Figured that's how it is with good things, whether it's art or bein' a decent human. There's more to it than just the words or actions, there's somethin' deeper, somethin' that moves ya.

That's why art and morals are so darn close, 'cause they both touch us in that special way, deep down inside. You can't explain it, but you sure feel it.

And when it comes to stories, well, that's somethin' else entirely.  Stories are like lookin' into the soul, they tell ya things you can't say out loud.

Germany today is a strong country with a unique culture all its own. You can feel it everywhere, from the mountains of München to the city of Kiel by the Baltic Sea. Whether you're in Köln on the Rhine River, in the heart of the country, or in Dresden on the Elbe, the German culture is unmistakable.

It shouldn't surprise us that Germany, as we know it today, came from many different tribes and groups.  

"Germania" is the old name for the land where the Germans came from.  

Scholars and historians still debate where the name "German" came from.  Some say it comes from a group called the Tungrians, who fought the Gauls a long time ago.  Others say Julius Caesar used the word "Germanus" to describe the tribes he fought across the Rhine River. He was trying to tell the difference between the Gauls, who he had conquered, and the Germans, who he hadn't. Some people think "German" came from a word the Gauls used to describe their neighbors.  Caesar himself wrote about the Germans in his writings about the Gallic Wars, saying they were constantly fighting with the Gauls.

There are other ideas too. Some think it comes from the spear they used in battle, called a "ger." Others think it comes from an old Irish word meaning "to shout," because the Germans were known for being loud. 

The Roman historian Tacitus wrote a book about the Germans called "De Origine et situ Germanorum," and in it, he said he thought the Germans were the original people of the land and hadn't mixed with other races. He thought people wouldn't have chosen to move to Germany, with its wild land and harsh weather, unless it was their home. 

The Romans did send troops to Germania for goods and to fight, but they didn't want to live there. 

The Germanic tribes began appearing near the Roman Empire in the first century. They lived on the borders and traded goods and even served in the Roman army.

Well, lemme tell ya, I was lookin' at this here mess, and my brain just wasn't catchin' on.  I was starin' at it, but it was like my mind was on vacation, ya know?  Just takin' it all in, but not really gettin' nothin' outta it.  Thoughts were poppin' in and out faster than a jackrabbit, never stickin' around long enough to make any sense.  It was like watchin' a movie on fast forward, seein' all the action but missin' the story.

Once, this artist buddy of mine, he told me to check out this book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain."  I always wanted to learn how to draw, ever since I was a little whippersnapper, and this book was supposed to teach ya everything, from how to hold a pencil right to how your brain sees lines and stuff.  One trick they teach is to put a square around whatever ya want to draw, like a frame, and that way, even if somethin's super complicated, ya can just focus on the basics.

Well, lookin' at this thing in front of me, I couldn't picture that frame, couldn't break it down like that.  I was just floored, man, overwhelmed.  Like, Picasso had his blue phase, Monet loved them green things, and all them fancy Renaissance painters, they used every color under the sun.  If I was gonna call myself an artist, this here was my start, my own masterpiece, "Work in Brown."  

So I picked up my tool of the trade, ya know, got my hand all ready, and I'm thinkin' this is gonna be the most creative moment of my life.  The water was swirlin' around, nice and smooth, clear as day.  Little bits of stuff were breakin' off, floatin' away.  But then, my hand gets all tense, shakin' a little, and BAM!  I slam the toilet handle again.  That brown package wouldn't budge, stuck like glue to the bottom.

I got my mop, standin' there with my tie feelin' like it was chokin' me, just starin' at this thing someone left behind.  A message for the poor saps who clean bathrooms at Rite Aid, I guess.  Flushed a couple more times, tried to get my mind back in the game, but then I just reached for the toilet paper, wrapped myself up like a goddamn mummy.  Standing up straight, bendin' over, I reach into the bowl, like a mama bird checkin' on her nest…

Now listen up, folks. Those young whippersnappers, they're gettin' killed behind the wheel somethin' fierce! Why? Well, their brains ain't fully cooked yet, ya know? It's like tryin' to run a marathon with a cold. They got no experience, nothin' but a learner's permit and a whole lotta bravado. 

I'm tellin' ya, those kids, they're like a bunch of chickens runnin' around a henhouse. They can't handle the pressure, especially when they got their buddies in the car.  Got a study done in California, shows the more passengers, the more accidents. Makes sense, right? 

They tryin' to fix things with these temporary licenses, but it's like puttin' a bandaid on a broken leg. We gotta go deeper, see? These kids, they crave that thrill, that rush. Like, they ain't even 18 yet and they're thinkin' they're invincible. This psychologist, Zuckerman, he says even 18 is too young.  

Listen, we gotta wait 'til they grow up a bit, ya know? Let 'em have their fun, but not behind the wheel. By the time the baby boomers' kids are old enough to drive, we'll be lookin' at a real mess. 

We need to make a law, a real law, not just some flimsy rule. Let 'em learn in school, but no drivin' 'til they're older. Maybe 19 or 20, when they've calmed down a little. Then, they can get their driver's permit, take some lessons, and show they're ready. 

It ain't rocket science. We gotta protect these kids. This ain't no joke.

So I was lookin' at all these old Edison movies, the Library of Congress has a bunch of 'em. I figured I'd check out the trick films, you know, the ones that play with your eyes.  There were fifteen of 'em, made between 1895 and 1901.  Mostly they just use cuttin' and pastin' together to make things look spooky or funny.  I kinda wanted to figure out how they did it, ya know, the tricks of the trade.

Most of these old trick films stick to the same kinda thing. They're filmed in a little stage-like set, with the camera just sittin' there, not movin' around. Like they're watchin' a play or somethin'.  They don't use any fancy camera tricks, just long shots where you can see the whole thing at once.  And they never get real close up on nothin'.   It's like they're tryin' to show you the whole picture, like you're in the front row of a theater.

Now, there are a few films, later on, that get a little wild and start usin' more than one shot.  But for the most part, they stick to this one-shot, one-movie deal.  So these films aren't real long, maybe a minute or two, just enough time for a quick trick or gag.  It's like a vaudeville act, y'know, quick and flashy.

But even though they only use one shot, sometimes they'll splice together a bunch of 'em to make it look like somethin' is apparin' or disappearin'.  Take that old film about Mary, Queen of Scots, for example. Looks like one shot, but if you really pay attention, you can see where they cut it together.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout this fella, John Taylor. He was a real firecracker when it came to this whole Republican thing, especially back in the day. You could tell he was a farmer, rough around the edges, but he knew his stuff.  This guy believed in freedom, plain and simple.  He thought the government shouldn't stick its nose in folks' business, especially when it came to how they made a livin'.  

See, John, he thought the United States had a real chance to do things right, build something special.  He figured we didn't have all that old-world baggage to hold us back, so we could make a system that worked for the people.  He was all about folks having the right to do their own thing, and he thought the government should stay outta the way.  

Now, this John, he believed in this whole "good and bad" thing, like everybody's got a little bit of both in 'em.  He thought the government needed to keep an eye on that bad stuff, make sure it didn't get outta control. But, he didn't want the government to be too powerful, ya know? He wanted to keep it small and simple, just like he liked his farm.  

John was a stickler for the Constitution, too.  He thought the government should only do what the Constitution said it could, and no more.  He didn't want some big, fancy government runnin' things, spendin' all our money and tellin' us what to do.  He thought the Founding Fathers had it right, and that's how we should keep it.

Listen, we had this thing goin' on, tryin' to get folks to use less cars and walk or bike more. Figured it'd be a hoot, right? But lemme tell ya, it was a real struggle.  We saw these numbers droppin' fast around December, like folks just forgot all about it. Makes sense, I guess. Winter's comin' on, folks are busy with school and Christmas, and then everyone's gone on break. Even I get lazy when it's cold and snowy! We tried to get folks back on track with a "Carpool Challenge" in March, and that helped a bit. But it's tough, you know? People just love their cars. It's kinda like what I said about my pool, doin' it yourself is cheaper, but it takes a lot more work.  Give folks a free hybrid car, now that's somethin' that might get them movin'! We gave out gift cards and stuff, but maybe we shoulda gone bigger, ya know?  We coulda had a raffle, a big ol' prize draw! Might've kept folks more interested.

You know how there's these things called ETFs, like investment clubs but fancier? They're supposed to be like a basket of stocks all rolled into one, kinda like a shortcut to owning a bunch of stuff at once. 

You get the good parts of owning a bunch of different stocks, but with less fuss.  It's cheaper than some other ways of investing, but you still gotta pay a little somethin' somethin' every time you buy or sell. 

The trick is, sometimes the "shortcut" ain't always the best shortcut.  Like, if you buy this ETF,  IHF, it's got a bunch of different stocks inside it, ten of 'em make up most of the deal.  So, I'm thinkin', maybe it's smarter to just buy those ten stocks straight up instead of through the ETF.  

We gotta figure out if buying the whole ETF is really better than buyin' those top ten stocks yourself.  It might sound complicated, but we're gonna look at how much money each stock in the ETF makes, and how risky it is. 

We'll see if buying the whole ETF is really worth it, or if you'd be better off picking the top ten stocks yourself.

So, this Poe fella, he wrote this poem called "Dream-Land", and he thinks it's pretty darn good.  In it, he uses this word "Thulé" a couple of times, and some smart guy named Mabbott says Poe probably got it from this old dude Virgil. Virgil wrote about an island called Thulé way up north, like beyond the edge of the world back then. Now, Virgil did use the word, but I bet Poe got it from a German writer named Goethe too.

See, Poe loved reading German stuff. And this Goethe guy, he wrote a famous play called "Faust",  about this guy who makes a deal with the devil.  There's this little poem inside "Faust" called "The King of Thulé", and it's about a king who loses his wife and goes totally bonkers. He drinks a whole lot, cries his eyes out, and finally decides to end it all. Kinda sounds like Poe's character in "Dream-Land",  don't it?  Maybe Poe was just channeling his own heartache through that poem.

Now, this "Faust" thing was also made into a play around the time Poe was writing "Dream-Land".  So there's that connection too.  Poe used "Thulé" two times in his other writings, and he booksends "Dream-Land" with it. It's almost like he's putting those poems together, like puzzle pieces. In "Dream-Land", the speaker talks about this dark, lonely place, haunted by dead friends, kinda like that king in "The King of Thulé" after he loses his wife.

So, you gotta remember, Goethe was a big deal back then, and Poe knew his work. Even if it was just because Poe liked this other guy, Tennyson, who also liked Goethe.  Poe probably saw a lot of Goethe's stuff floating around.

So there's this lady, Jennifer Palmer, who fell in a grocery store 'cause some applesauce was spilled.  She's sayin' the manager, this guy Martin, knew about the spill 'cause his employees told him about it twice, but he just ignored it 'cause he was eatin' dinner.  Palmer got hurt pretty bad, and now she wants the store to pay her some extra money called "punitive damages" 'cause she says Martin acted mean and reckless. 

Now, the judge ain't gonna just throw out her case right away.  To get those extra damages, Palmer gotta prove Martin knew his actions could hurt someone - like, he knew it was dangerous to leave that applesauce there.  She can say that Martin shoulda known 'cause people had been slipping and falling in the store all year.   

Whether or not Martin was bein' straight up mean is a bit harder to prove. But, if six folks already fell and he still didn't clean up, it ain't lookin' good for him. 

It all went down back in '09. A worker named Rich told Martin about the spill, but Martin said he didn't have time 'cause he was eatin'.  Another worker, Mary, told him again, and Martin said the same thing. Then, an hour later, Palmer went and slipped and hurt her back. 

Now, Palmer's sayin' she wants money for her hurt and for Martin bein' a real jerk. California law kinda says if someone acts mean or reckless, they can pay extra damages.  It ain't easy to prove, but Palmer thinks she can show that Martin knew what he was doin' was wrong.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'. Back when I took that Islam class at CBC, almost four years ago, we were always talkin' about whether Islam was a bad religion or not.  Seems like that question's even more important now than it was back then. You see, since 9/11, the news folks went from thinkin' Islam was the devil to thinkin' it was all sunshine and roses.  I bet you wouldn't have seen a guy like Barack Obama, with his Muslim family, runnin' for president back in 2001.

Now, this book about Muhammad, well, it's somethin' else. See, back in the day, I thought Muhammad was a real tough guy, conquerin' tribes and makin' 'em turn Muslim or else. But this book, it paints him like some kinda martyr, misunderstood and humble.  Folks came to him all on their own, seein' the light, like they were drawn to him.

And wouldn't ya know it, there's some similarities between how Muhammad did things and what Jesus did. Like that time he turned some mutton and milk into enough for forty guys?  Sounds like somethin' Jesus woulda done, don't it?  It makes me think they're tryin' to make Muhammad look like some kinda holy man, like he didn't need to prove nothin'.  It's kinda sneaky, ya know, makin' him seem like he's stealin' Jesus' thunder.

Plus, they got all these stories about folks convertin' on their own, like they were just seein' the truth.  But a lot of these stories are second-hand, like they heard it from someone who heard it from someone else.  That makes it all kinda fishy to me.  It's like they're tryin' to make it sound more official, but it just makes me wonder.

What really ticks me off is how they try to make Muhammad out to be this gentle, wise, and kinda lovable guy. But history tells a different story.  Was Muhammad really that nice?  I wonder if Muslims today even know the real story about how he came to power.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'.  Ever since Jesus hung up his sandals, folks been puttin' their own spin on what he taught.  Like, it's gone way off track, ya know?  The world's gettin' all fancy and progressive, but those stuck in their ways, they ain't gonna like it.  But those folks ain't gonna be the ones callin' the shots.  

Mark my words, folks are gonna start lookin' back, tryin' to figure out what Jesus really meant, ya know, cuttin' through all the fluff that's been piled on over the years.  It might take a while, maybe decades, maybe even longer, but it's gonna happen.  We're gonna see Christianity go back to its roots, like we're rewindin' a tape.  It's gonna be a whole lotta "unlearnin'" goin' on.

And this ain't just some hippie dream.  The churches will still be there, leadin' the way, but things are gonna be different.  Folks are gonna start thinkin' alike more, like a big ol' family reunion.  Forget all this different denominations and whatnot,  we're all gonna be singin' from the same hymn book.

History's full of these kinda turnarounds, ya know?  Just like the Romans used to hate Christians, then turned around and became Christians themselves.  And look at us, used to have slaves, now we got black folks runnin' the show.  This time, it's gonna be the churches, goin' back to basics, forgettin' all the extra stuff.

Now, this ain't gonna happen overnight. It'll take some doin',  especially with all those folks who take everythin' about the Bible literally.  But we gotta understand what Jesus was really tryin' to say.

See, way back when, before Jesus came along, there was Judaism.  They believed in one God, and they had their holy books, just like Christians do now.  Back then, they weren't all on the same page though, had all sorts of different groups, just like today.

Listen, folks, this whole "The Jungle" thing, it just shows how greedy folks can be. They only care about themselves and makin' a buck, ain't nothin' else that matters.  See, those factory owners, they're all about gettin' bigger and richer, don't give a hoot about the folks workin' for 'em or the mess they're makin'.  Sinclair, he paints a picture of this smoke-filled town, all dirty and nasty, and the bosses, they don't care a lick. They just keep pumpin' out the goods, makin' money, and forgettin' about the people and the planet. 

It's the same with the workers. These bosses, they treat 'em like dirt. They work 'em to the bone, don't pay 'em right, and when they ain't needin' 'em no more, they just toss 'em out on the street.  Back then, there weren't no rules to protect folks, so these factory bosses could do whatever they wanted.

It's like sayin' these workers were slaves, only they weren't chained up. They had no say in nothin', nothin' but to do as they were told. This whole system, it's just plain wrong. It ain't right to treat people like that.

This here writer guy, he's got a way of makin' ya feel somethin' about what he's talkin' about. Some ways work better than others, ya know?  Like that F. Scott fella, he wrote this book called "The Great Gatsby" and he uses all sorts of tricks to get ya feelin' a certain way. Sometimes he'll put words together that don't usually go together, just to make somethin' feel a certain way. Other times, he'll pick an object, like a color, and give it a special meaning, then use that meaning later on to make ya think about somethin' else. This fella, he really liked to use colors, like gold, green, white, gray, and red and pink. In his book "The Great Gatsby," he's got all these special meanings for these colors, especially white and gray and red and pink. Then, he uses those meanings later on to give ya a certain feelin' about important stuff in the story.

See, he makes white and gray mean kinda like sameness, like everything's the same. White is a bit fancier, more high-class, and gray is more like old and worn out. He starts showin' ya this right at the beginning of the book, with lots of white and gray. Daisy and Jordan, they're always wearin' white, like, all the time. Everyone's wearin' white: Nick's in "white flannels" at Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine's all "powdered milky white." The only time folks aren't wearin' white is when Nick's gettin' his first look at Gatsby's party, and everything's all "gaudy with primary colors." He keeps usin' these colors for everyday stuff too, like when Nick goes to work, he goes down "the white chasms of lower New York."  People's names at Gatsby's party are all "gray names" on Nick's list. Catherine's apartment is just one slice in a big "white cake" of buildings—it's all the same. He even calls plain people and places white or gray, like Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" together, and there are "gray cars" and "gray land" in the Valley of Ashes. Even the "Italian child" on the railroad is "gray," and the dog-seller is "a gray old man."

After he's used white and gray enough, he starts usin' them to show that somethin' ain't that important, or that it's all the same. He does this with Daisy, for instance. After a long time without seein' much white or gray, he writes about Daisy bein' "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster." Now, Daisy starts feelin' less like a real person and more like somethin' Gatsby just wants, somethin' that's kinda uniform. He keeps usin' white and gray around Daisy to make ya feel that way. Like, there's a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar," and she's wearin' white again before Tom and Gatsby have that big fight.

Well, down in San Diego, the weather's so nice and sunny, they grow all sorts of good stuff. Tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, peppers - you name it! Seems like everyone's going crazy for organic food down there, with folks waitin' forever to get their hands on it. Organic eggs and milk are real popular too. And get this, a lot of those organic farms let you come visit, take a hike, go birdwatching - kinda like a mini-vacation.

You know, it'd be a good deal for the landowner, makin' money but also helpin' out the environment. They could get some help from the government for makin' things better for the wildlife, while they teach folks about farms and sell some organic goodies. 

 Now, growin' organic ain't all sunshine and roses, though. It takes a lot more work to keep those bugs and weeds away without chemicals, and sometimes you lose more crops. But on the bright side, it makes things better for all the plants and animals around. They're sayin' you can have more bees and butterflies and all sorts of critters when you don't use all those nasty chemicals.

So, this landowner's got a real opportunity. They've got this 160-acre piece of land near Potrero, California, with chaparral, grassland, and oak trees. It's right next to the Cleveland National Forest, which is full of all sorts of critters, some of 'em endangered, like the kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. This land's been used for farms and ranches for ages, so it's got a history too.

Seems like this landowner's lookin' for ways to make money while keepin' things natural. They're lookin' into government programs to help them out and seein' what other organic farms in the area are doin'. It's a tough job, but it sounds like they're up for the challenge!

Listen, culture, it's a real big deal when you're tryin' to talk business, ya know? It ain't just some one-size-fits-all thing, like sayin' all folks from one place are the same.  It's more like, understandin' how people from different places tick, what makes 'em tick. You can't just go in there thinkin' everyone's gonna play by the same rules, 'cause they ain't. If you're from Texas and talkin' to folks from, say, New York, well, you gotta remember you're speakin' different languages, kinda.  It ain't just the words, but the whole way you think about things, what's important, what you consider right or wrong.

Now, I ain't sayin' you gotta be best buddies with everyone, but a little respect goes a long way. Learnin' about their customs, their history, even their prejudices, it all helps. Don't go in there tryin' to change 'em, just try to understand 'em. Especially if you're the one who needs somethin' from 'em.  If you're in their neck of the woods, show 'em you respect their way of doin' things.

And listen, culture ain't just about countries, it's about companies too. Some companies are all about workin' hard, long hours, others are more laid back.  Pay attention to how they dress, how they talk, who they hire.  It all tells you somethin' about their culture.  Even in America, different companies are different.  You gotta figure out who you're dealin' with and play their game.

But the most important thing is understandin' their values, what they believe in. If they value savin' face or keepin' things peaceful, you ain't gonna wanna embarrass them in a negotiation. If they're all about gettin' the best deal, you gotta be ready to play tough.

So, before you sit down at the table, do your homework. Learn about your opponent, their culture, their values. It'll make all the difference in the world.

Well now, these two fellas, Anselm and Aquinas, both want to prove there's a God, right?  They both think there's a God, just like that fella in the Bible said, "The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’"   See, they both agree on this God thing, so we gotta figure out who's got the better argument. Now, I'm gonna be honest, neither one of 'em really convinces me completely. 

Anselm, he figures God's already in our heads, y'know? Like, we gotta know He's there 'cause we can think about Him.  It's like, if you can think about somethin', it's gotta exist, right?  That's kinda how he sees it. Kinda like how you know your momma's always gonna nag you, even if you ain't see her in a while. You just know she's there, even if she ain't. Anselm's sayin' God's like that.

Now, Aquinas, he's a different kind of bird. He's all about logic and facts, y'know, like a good businessman. He says we can prove God exists by lookin' at the world around us, seein' how things work and figuring out there gotta be a big guy behind it all. He's got five different reasons, all based on somethin' he calls "logical necessity." Like, if you got a puzzle with a bunch of pieces, and you know there's one missin', you can figure out what that piece looks like just by lookin' at the rest, right? Aquinas is sayin' it's the same with God. We can see how things work, and we know He's gotta be there.

Listen up, folks! Way back in the day, a long time ago, this dude was born.  He grew up to be a prince, but he wasn't your typical prince. See, this guy, who everyone calls Buddha, decided to ditch all the fancy stuff and figure out life.  He got really smart, you know, enlightened, and started teaching folks how to be better people. That's how Buddhism started, and the most hardcore version of it is called Theravada.  

This religion's been around for like 2,500 years, and it's changed a bit since Buddha was alive.  Like, in Sri Lanka, these monks and regular folks have this water-cutting ceremony every year. Buddha never talked about that, but it's a big deal for them. That's just one example, see?  From the little stuff to the big ideas, things have shifted over time.

The monks and the regular folks who follow Buddhism have had to tweak their beliefs a little.  Sometimes it's because of outside stuff, sometimes it's because of stuff inside the religion itself. Sometimes it's good, sometimes it's bad, like a two-sided coin.

Now, let me break down some words we'll be using a lot. We got "inside" and "outside" forces. Inside comes from people who are already Buddhists, whether they're monks or not. Outside comes from people who aren't Buddhists. We also got "hostile" and "benign." Hostile means something bad, something that wants to hurt Buddhism. Benign means it doesn't care about hurting or helping, but it might end up doing one or the other by accident.

First things first, let's talk about what Buddhists believe. They find peace in the "triple gem" – Buddha himself, his teachings (the Dhamma), and the community of Buddhists (the Sangha). The Dhamma is like a big library of Buddhist texts, divided into three parts.  There's the Sutta Pitaka, which is like the main stories. Then there's the Vinaya Pitaka, which has all the rules for monks and nuns. And finally, there's the Abhidhamma Pitaka, which gets all philosophical and talks about things like "no self," "suffering," and "everything changes."  

The Buddhists say that understanding these things is the key to stopping the cycle of death and rebirth (that's called Sansara).  By letting go of greed, anger, and delusion, you can become enlightened and free from suffering.

They also have these rules called the "five precepts" for regular folks. They're basically: don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't cheat, and don't get drunk. Monks and nuns have way more rules, of course.

The most important idea in Buddhism is the "four noble truths."  First, life is full of suffering. Second, we suffer because we cling to things. Third, we can stop suffering. And fourth, there's a way to stop suffering. It's all about understanding these truths and living your life accordingly.

Listen up, folks!  America and Mexico, they had a right ol' grudge match goin' on for a good long while, near 'bout 57 years, from back in 1836 all the way to 1893.  These two were like cats and dogs, always at each other's throats.  The biggest blow up was that Mexican-American War back in the 1840s.  America went in there, kicked some Mexican tail, and took Texas and all that fancy Southwest land for itself.  And they weren't just brawlin' over land, neither.  They butted heads 'bout religion, culture, and all sorts of other stuff.  It's like when your neighbor is always stealin' your lawn ornaments and talkin' smack about your grillin' skills.

You see this kinda rivalry pop up all the time between neighbors.  They're right there, sniffin' each other out, always lookin' for a reason to squabble.  America and Mexico, they're like that.  Some folks say America's always got problems with Mexico and Cuba, more'n any other country down south.  Maybe it's 'cause they're so close, always rubbin' elbows.

Religion, that's another thing that got 'em riled up.  Back in the day, America didn't much like Catholicism.  Sound familiar?  It's like the Cold War, but instead of communism, it was religion.  You had Americans and Mexicans, both holdin' onto their beliefs tight, like a dog with a bone. 

They went at it somethin' fierce, these two.  Border skirmishes, bandits runnin' amok, it was a mess.  But eventually, things cooled down.  Mexico got real reliant on America for stuff, and America's focus shifted from takin' land to makin' money.   They found a way to get along, after all that ruckus.

Fifteen years ago, somethin' hit me outta nowhere, like a ton of bricks. I got this sickness, one I never even knew existed. Back then I was a nurse, ya know? I'd always figured that'd be my gig - everyone's gotta get sick sometime, right?  Always thought I'd be a scientist or a writer, maybe both, but I went with the safe bet. "Nursing's a sure thing," folks kept sayin', "you'll always have work." So, here I was, 46, single, and nothin' in the bank, suddenly unable to work. This illness, it messed me up good.  Fifteen years on disability, and I'm down to nothin'.  Barely gettin' by, every day's a fight, like I'm right back in that insecure childhood.  Life ain't solid anymore, not one bit. But there's one thing I know for sure: I couldn't have made it this far without my family and a few good friends.  Trust me, when life throws ya a curveball, you don't feel so tough.

See, life throws you curveballs, big and small. You can plan all ya want, but some things, you just can't handle alone.  

Folks on the right, they talk about "rugged individualism," how that built this country. But back in the day, it wasn't just grit that got 'em through. It was lookin' out for each other, sharin' what you had. Those pioneers who crossed the Rockies, they didn't make it by go'in it alone. They stuck together.


So, yeah, be prepared.  I am. I got a disaster kit, first aid, water purifier, even plastic sheeting for the windows if somethin' nasty ever happens. Flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, canned goods – the whole shebang.  If you got the land, grow your own food, learn to can it. Good idea, especially if you got a wood stove.  But here's the thing, don't forget about your neighbors. Get to know 'em.

Alright, so ya see these fancy scientists, they're tryin' to figure out how critters change over time, right?  It's like, why do they look the way they do?  Is there some kinda rulebook for how evolution works?  Back in 1917, this fella D'Arcy Thompson said we're barely scratchin' the surface of understandin' how to talk about this stuff with numbers.  And ya know what?  He's still right!

But now, folks are usin' math to try and figure out how shells on these squirmy sea critters called mollusks grow.  It's like, take a picture of the shell at different stages, then use a computer program to see what might happen if it grew in different ways.  Kinda like buildin' a model, ya know?  They're callin' it "mathematical modeling," which sounds fancy, but it's just tryin' to make sense of how things change.

Imagine a shell like a snail's house, but instead of brick, it's made of this hard stuff.  It spirals around and around, like a ramp windin' up.  Each turn is called a whorl, and the center is called the columella.  Some shells grow faster in some parts than others, and you can see the lines where the whorls join up.  The biggest part is the last one, called the body whorl.

Now, picture a whole bunch of these shells, like a family history of snails.  Scientists look at how they're all different, how they grew, and try to figure out what made them change.  They're usin' math to help 'em see the patterns and make predictions.  It's like a big puzzle, but instead of pieces, it's shells!

Listen, Indonesia's been doin' alright for the last ten years, y'know? They're gettin' closer to meetin' those fancy Millennium Development Goals, like makin' sure folks have clean water and bathrooms. But when it comes to takin' care of babies and moms, they're fallin' behind.  We gotta do better, ya hear? 

Now, they're braggin' about more folks havin' babies with a healthcare worker around. But lemme tell ya, a lot of 'em are just midwives, not real doctors. So what good is that when somethin' goes wrong?  And the thing about kids gettin' sick with the trots, well, they're not seein' doctors much anymore. It's sad, really. And don't even get me started on how they're treatin' moms after they give birth. Ain't right.

C-sections are too low, especially in the sticks. It's like they're forgettin' folks out there in the country.  Those folks in the cities, they got it good. But the poor? They ain't got a chance. They can't afford healthcare, you see?

So what do we do? Should we just throw money at specific problems, or should we fix the whole darn healthcare system? 

Programmatic stuff sounds good, like targetin' just newborn care. It's easier to manage and you see results faster. But here's the rub: if you focus too much on one thing, you forget about everything else. And everyone wants to work on the hot topic, so the rest gets neglected.  It's like a tug-of-war, ya know?

Victorian books are all about the little details and they really love to talk about fancy rich people. But there are a couple of books from that time, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, that don't really follow those rules. They've got this mystery going on and some weird stuff happens, which is different from most books back then.  This mystery stuff helps us understand the characters better, like what they're really thinking and feeling.  

Here's a little bit from Oliver Twist that shows what I mean:

“'He felt like he was stuck between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing and yelling.  He could even hear them talking, even though he wasn't really there. Then suddenly, he heard a gunshot, and everything around him exploded into chaos. Lights were flashing, people were screaming, and someone grabbed him and started dragging him away.  Through it all, he felt this awful, nagging pain that wouldn't go away.” (Dickens, 220)

These books use mystery and strange stuff, like dreams, to show you what's going on inside the characters' heads.  In Oliver Twist, these weird dreams tell us about Oliver's pain and how confused he is about what's happening around him. When Oliver gets shot, he has a dream about it again in Chapter 28, and it's like he's reliving the whole thing.  It shows how much pain he's in and how helpless he feels.  He can't even see who's dragging him away because he's so overwhelmed.  Oliver doesn't feel in control of anything, and it makes you wonder if someone is making bad things happen to him on purpose. This shooting shows how much control Oliver has lost.  He doesn't even try to fight back, like maybe someone has broken his spirit and made him give up.


“Time just flew by.  One minute it was day, the next it was night again. Night felt long and scary because it was so quiet, but it also felt short because it went by so quickly.”

So, lemme tell ya 'bout this kid, Adrian. Couple years back, I was workin' at this after-school thing, helpin' out little kids with their schoolwork. Now, I was pretty good with English and readin', but this kid Adrian, he was givin' me fits.  He was in third or fourth grade, somethin' like that.  Seemed like he understood some words fine, but others, he'd butcher 'em somethin' fierce. It was like he were speakin' a different language, but he talked perfect English! I was scratchin' my head, wonderin' what was goin' on.  He was Latino,  that much I knew, but his English was spot on. We went round and round, but nothin' seemed to click. Then one day, Adrian's mama came to pick him up. Now, she didn't speak a lick of English, only Spanish.  I was just learnin' a few words myself, but we managed to get by.  That's when it hit me like a ton of bricks – the kid could read fine, he just didn't know his ABCs!  Maybe it wasn't so much a problem with readin', but more like a language problem, you know? I dunno if it helped him much in the long run, but I sure hope he's doin' alright now.

This whole thing got me thinkin' 'bout how tough it can be for kids who don't speak English well.  We gotta do somethin' about it, right here in California, where there are so many different languages.  It ain't always as clear-cut as you think. Even if a kid speaks English good, readin' it can still be a real pain. 

So, what's the answer? Well, Adrian's case was kinda simple – he just needed help with learnin' the alphabet and how to pronounce the letters. But for kids who barely speak English, it's a whole different ball game. There ain't just one magic bullet. We gotta try different things,  like dual language programs,  where kids learn in both English and their own language.  We gotta have more ESL classes, and maybe even some private tutors. It takes a whole lotta effort, but we gotta do it. 

First things first, let's talk about these dual language programs. They're great for all kids, not just those who speak Spanish. Lots of folks are scared of 'em, thinkin' they waste money and don't help most kids. But that's just plain wrong. If we used these programs more often, every kid would benefit.

Now, I ain't sayin' every teacher has to be bilingual. That'd be crazy! But we could have special helpers, tutors, whatever ya call 'em, who speak both languages. That'd make a big difference, I tell ya!

Well, lemme tell ya, from the time we're little whippersnappers, folks are always talkin' 'bout somethin' bigger than us, somethin' we can't even wrap our heads around. Some go to church, some go to temple, some just try to figure it out on their own.  Lotta folks just go with what their parents taught 'em, but some folks, they say "Nah, ain't nothin' out there but what we can see right here."  Might change their minds later, but that's life, ain't it?  We all lookin' for somethin', somethin' to make sense of it all, a light in the darkness, you know what I mean?

My old man, he was a simple fella. One time, I asked him what his favorite bird was and he said a cardinal.  We were sittin' on the porch, rain beatin' down like a drum, smokin' cigarettes.  He looked out at the rain, kinda lost in thought, like he was seein' somethin' only he could see.  He'd gotten real thin, clothes hangin' off him like a sack of potatoes.  His hair was thin too, lettin' the light shine through.  He wouldn't look at me, kept his eyes on the rain.  I felt kinda lost, scared even, 'cause I didn't know how to tell him I was gonna miss him somethin' fierce. Sayin' it out loud would make it real, and that was somethin' neither of us wanted. So I just wrapped my arms around him, sat back down, scooted my chair closer, and joined him in starin' at the rain.

That was June. My dad passed away in December, just five days after my 22nd birthday. The chemo and radiation, it didn't stop the pain, just dragged it on a little longer. Doctors said he wouldn't make it past a certain point, but he hung on.  I couldn't figure out what good it did, just made things harder.  I thought, "What kinda God lets this happen?"  In the dead of night, I didn't even pray.  If there was a God out there, I figured he'd stopped listenin' a long time ago.

I didn't wanna watch him go, so I didn't.  Couldn't stand to see the life that gave me life slip away.  I wanted to remember him for the good times, not the last days.  Besides, I knew him better than anyone else, better than his own family.  I knew he wouldn't want me there, watchin' him die.  So I curled up in bed for three days, waitin' for the news.

Alright, so this "Gothic Novel" thing, it's kinda like a mix-up, y'know?  Like, it's old and new at the same time. This writer, Ian Watt, he called it an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'".  Some folks say Gothic stories ain't got no depth, while others think they're somethin' special, like they make ya feel somethin' real deep down. 

This first Gothic story, "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, it took bits and pieces from old stories and new ones to make somethin' brand new.  Walpole, he used stuff from old plays and then mixed it up with how folks were writin' stories back then, and called it a "Gothic Story".  He liked usin' stuff from the days of castles and knights, even though back then, folks thought all that was just old hat. They were all about bein' "modern" and fancy.

But here's the thing - Gothic stories got this mix of old and new that made 'em stick around for a long time. They're like a time capsule, y'know?  You read 'em now, and they feel old, but they also feel kinda fresh, like somethin' new.

One of the big ideas in Gothic stories is this thing called "Chivalry". Back in the olden days, folks were all about knights and how they were supposed to be brave and good.  Walpole, he wrote "The Castle of Otranto" when things were kinda messed up politically, and he thought maybe folks weren't so chivalrous anymore. So, he wrote about these knights, like this guy Frederic, to show what a real knight should be like.

Let me tell ya, this supply chain thing, it's like a big ol' recipe for gettin' stuff from point A to point B. You got your customer orderin' somethin', and then it's a whole chain reaction, ya know? Raw materials gotta get gathered, stuff gets made, then shipped out to the customer.  This fella, Keith Oliver, back in '82, he came up with the name "Supply Chain Management."  He figured out it's all about plannin' this whole shebang, makin' sure it runs smooth, and gettin' what folks want, quick and easy.

There's six main parts to this whole thing, kinda like the ingredients in that recipe.  You got production, supply, inventory, where to put things, how to move 'em, and information - gotta keep track of it all!

Production's the first step, the foundation, like the flour in a cake.  You gotta figure out what folks want,  what they're buyin', like lookin' at the whole market, seein' what's hot.  Then, you decide what to make, how much, where to make it, and make sure the stuff comes out right, like bakin' that cake just right.  Got to be careful, 'cause if somethin's off, it can cost ya big time. Remember when I worked at Walmart and Target? They had all these rules, like a recipe book, for everything! Made sure things ran smooth, no confusion.

Then you got supply, figuring out where you're gonna get your ingredients from.  You might have different parts of your business doin' different things, like makin' the cake batter and the frosting.  You gotta decide who does what best, maybe even gettin' help from other folks, like outsourcing the frosting.  That way, you can get it done faster, cheaper, and still make a darn good cake!

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'. This Ellen Page, she's a real go-getter, standin' on a street corner with a sign sayin' Hitler's still alive in Burma. Now, Burma, that's a rough place, ruled by a bunch of tough guys who took over back in '62. See, they don't like folks speakin' up, kinda like my old man when I was a kid. 

A few years back, some monks decided they'd had enough, so they started marchin', wearin' their yellow robes, and callin' it the "Saffron Revolution."  It's like when I get mad about the price of beans, but instead of yellin', they're marchin' and stuff.

Well, the government didn't like it much. They started crackin' down, hurtin' folks, even killin' a few.  They don't want anyone messin' with their power, just like those guys back in the day with big hats and fancy words, tryin' to tell everyone what to think.  

This ain't nothin' new, though. Seems like folks in power always wanna be in charge, no matter what. They act like they're gods, like that emperor in Rome or that fella in Japan who thought he was a phone company CEO. Even our own president, he hangs out with those guys who think they know everything.

You remember what happened in China, back in '89?  Students and folks like that, they got together, and the government, well, let's just say they didn't like it much. And then there was Rwanda, where they went after folks just 'cause they were different.

Listen, it all boils down to this: folks in power don't like it when you challenge 'em. They wanna be the boss, call all the shots.  It's like tryin' to tell my dog what to do, only a lot more serious.

Now listen, this Duke Ellington fella, he was a real deal jazz cat. He stuck around for a long time, and that means he got real good at making his band sound good. He might not have played the piano loud in all his songs, but boy, could he write some fancy tunes!  He made music where each guy in the band could show off their skills, but he also knew how to get everyone playing together like a well-oiled machine. He could make the whole band sound like one big, amazing voice.  

This one book about music says Ellington was real good at using voices in jazz, like makin' 'em sound like instruments. He had this song called "Creole Love Call" where the voice ain't singin' words, it's just makin' sounds, like a real instrument.  He was all about givin' each musician a chance to shine, and this song shows that. It's slow and bluesy, and it goes through these different parts where different guys get to show off.  You got the voice talkin' back and forth with the wind instruments, then the trumpet plays a solo, all smooth and bluesy. Then the clarinet takes over, all high and fancy. It's like a conversation between all these different sounds. And then the whole band jumps in, makin' it all come together.

He did the same thing in other songs, too, like "Hot and Bothered" and "It Don't Mean a Thing." He'd use a trumpet player and a singer, makin' their voices sound like instruments, and then he'd have a trombone player start a melody, makin' it all sound real special.  Duke Ellington, he knew how to make jazz sound good, and he did it for a long, long time.

She'd always felt like somethin' was missin'. Like there was a hole inside her that nothin' could fill. This feelin' started when she was about fourteen, just gettin' into all that teenage stuff. And it was still there three years later, when she turned seventeen. By then, she'd figured out she wanted some kinda person in her life, not just some shiny thing. But she just couldn't find a boy who caught her eye. A few guys tried to court her, all awkward and clumsy, but none of 'em did nothin' for her. She spent a lot of time wonderin' why this was happenin' to her, tryin' to figure out what was makin' her so different from other girls her age. She had some ideas, but nothin' that really made sense. So she just kept livin' her life, always wonderin' about this empty space inside her.

Life at home was usually pretty peaceful. Her folks were good, calm people. They never fought with each other, and rarely argued with her either. The only time they'd butt heads was when she tried to act more independent, showin' off her own spunky personality. She was the daughter of two mellow folks, but she sure brought the energy, always up for somethin' fun. Everyone liked her 'cause she was sweet and fun-lovin'.

But today wasn't a peaceful day. She was moseying from room to room, tryin' to find some inspiration, when she heard a little scream from the kitchen. It was her mom's voice, and she sounded scared.  She bolted into the kitchen, worryin' somethin' awful. "Mom! Mom, what's wrong?" She saw her mom on the floor, lookin' pale and in pain, whimperin', "Ow," with every breath. She rushed to her mom's side and touched her gently. "Ouch... sweety, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." She was speakin' in short bursts, and it was clear she was hurt bad. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where I need to pick you up." Her mom pointed, and her daughter, strong from all those self-defense classes, knew just what to do. She carried her mom to the car, set her down gently in the back seat, and drove like a bat outta hell.

The hospital smelled like antiseptic and sickness, but all she could think about was helpin' her mom. She rushed her inside, yellin' for a doctor. A bunch of worried faces gathered around, and someone quickly got a gurney and laid her mom down. They took her away for treatment, leavin' her daughter sittin' there, worry gnawin' at her insides.

Turns out, her mom had fallen off a step stool while reachin' for a vase high up on a shelf.

This here study's tryin' to show that eatin' like folks in the Mediterranean, you know, that "Mediterranean Diet" stuff, keeps your ticker tickin' good and helps you avoid strokes. They got this fancy name for it, "alternate Mediterranean diet" or somethin', but it's all about eatin' your veggies, fruits, nuts, and fish, and cuttin' back on the meat and greasy stuff. A little vino ain't gonna hurt neither.

See, folks have been sayin' for a while now that this Mediterranean eatin' helps keep you healthy, but nobody really focused on strokes before. This study followed a bunch of nurses for 20 years, ask'em what they ate every few years, and low and behold, the ones who ate the most Mediterranean, they had less heart problems and strokes. 

They measured all sorts of things too, like how much they weighed, if they smoked, if they took vitamins, and if they were hoppin' around or sittin' on their duffs. Then they crunched the numbers and found that the more Mediterranean you ate, the less likely you were to have a heart attack or stroke. Pretty simple, really.

Well, lemme tell ya, back in 2007, this whole country went belly up.  Jobs disappeared faster than a shot of whiskey, the housing market crashed harder than a drunk at a rodeo, and all them big fancy companies were left lookin' like a dog that ate a whole watermelon.  This mess ain't gone away yet, so we gotta ask ourselves, what in tarnation happened and how do we fix it?

See, this whole financial crisis was like a bad case of the clap, caught by them politicians makin' decisions that were about as smart as a possum in a headlock. They pushed banks and folks to give out loans like candy at Halloween, even to folks who couldn't afford a bag of chips. And these fancy folks at Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, they took these loans and bundled them up into these complicated things called CDO's and CDS'. When folks started missin' their payments, the banks were left holdin' the bag, and the whole dang economy went kablooey!

This whole mess started back in '99, when President Clinton was tryin' to get re-elected. He wanted folks to like him, so he loosened up the rules on givin' out loans. It was like lettin' a bunch of toddlers loose with a whole candy store, only instead of candy, it was loans. And just like a toddler with a candy store, it all ended in a sticky mess.

Then they started creatin' these newfangled mortgages, like adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and these things called CDO's. They were all fancy words for makin' things even more complicated, and it was like tangled fishing line, just makin' the whole mess worse. Folks were borrowin' money they didn't have, and the housing market got all inflated like a hot air balloon.  

And then, just like a balloon with a hole in it, the bubble burst. All them banks that bought these fancy mortgage packages were left holdin' the bag, and the whole country went into a tailspin.

Alright, listen up, ya'll. This here's about exposition, that part of a story where you gotta show off your fancy writer's skills, or else your readers might just fall asleep faster'n a catfish in a mud puddle.  I'm talkin' 'bout the stuff that makes 'em wanna slam that "Back" button harder'n a slammed truck door.  Even ol' Dr. Merlin, she gets frustrated with Too Much Information. Not the fun kind, mind you, the kinda info that makes ya wanna scream, "Get to the point, ya dang story!"

Now, you folks know the golden rule, "Show, don't tell," right? But even I stumble sometimes, spillin' out pages and pages of nothin' happenin', or worse, too darn much happenin'. That's exposition, my friends. It's like that little devil whisperin' in your ear, tellin' ya to get all the backstory outta the way so you can get to the good stuff.  But hold your horses! Don't go tellin' your readers every darn thing about every character's childhood, got it?

Exposition is like that character in a movie who just lays it all out, spoutin' info like a broken record.  Or, in a story, it's the author doin' the talkin', layin' it all on thick.

Let me give ya an example. Imagine a story where the heroine met her hubby in a fancy place, got hitched in a big ol' ceremony, and then BAM! He's murdered right in front of her. You wouldn't wanna read two pages of nothin' but tellin' about that, would ya?  You'd expect somethin' more, somethin' with heart.  Show me the husband's love for his wife through his words and actions. Show me how he changed her life.  Make me feel somethin'!

Don't just tell me they met, got married, and he died. Give me the juicy details!  

See, that's what exposition is all about. You gotta give your readers somethin' to sink their teeth into. Don't be stingy with the details, folks!

Man, I watched a couple of news things from Columbus, Ohio the other day. 

First up was NBC 4, live this mornin' (August 13th, 2011). They had this story 'bout a fella in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife real bad. Didn't say her name, but the guy's name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot, and lemme tell ya, the dude looked like a snake in a Sunday suit! They only talked about it for, like, two minutes, sayin' he stabbed her a bunch of times and got hauled off. Seemed about right to me, givin' it a couple of minutes while they figured things out.

Next, they talked about this Travis Buyers, 18 years old, got shot real bad in the Sharon Woods area. No one knew who did it, SWAT was on the case. I gotta say, they didn't spend much time on this one. You know why? I bet it's 'cause this fella was black, or maybe he lived in a black neighborhood. It's like the news forgets folks like that got problems too. If a white kid got hurt, they'd be all over it, but if it's a black person, they barely even mention it. 

Then they talked about a bullet hole in one of them Med-Flight helicopters. Said it was a .22 from a rifle. They were offerin' five grand for any tips that led to the jerk who shot it.

They threw in a quickie about the rain comin' this weekend, said it'd be in the eighties, yadda yadda. Just teasin' ya to keep watchin', I guess.

They also had this story about a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road. They said the robber was a dark-skinned black man, wearin' a hoodie, about six feet tall and 150 pounds. Seemed kinda weird to me how much they hammered on about him bein' black.

And finally, they talked about this Rene Rodriguez, a drug dealer from Texas who got caught slingin' weed to Ohio. He got 300 months, which is 25 years, right?  They kept sayin' 300 months, like it was supposed to sound scarier.  And they mentioned he was Hispanic, but what does that have to do with anything?

Brothers, man, they got this bond, you know? Like, it's unbreakable, like somethin' you can't explain. It's got all kinds of stuff in it, love, yeah, but also pride, jealousy, even mean stuff sometimes. You know, brothers, they get each other, more than anybody else. It's like lookin' in a mirror, seein' yourself but somehow different, you know? And when things get tough, that bond, it really shows its true colors, good or bad.  It ain't always pretty, but it's real.  This story, "The Scarlet Ibis", it's all about that, about these two brothers and all the crazy feelings they got for each other.

They're runnin' around this beautiful place, but they're on a trip that ain't gonna end well. There's this bitter disappointment, like, they're both tryin' so hard but it ain't workin' out. Then there's this pride, this big ol' mess of pride, and it all comes to a head. In the end, only one brother makes it out alive.  

The story tells you about these emotions through the main guy, Doodle, and how he acts.  And it also tells you about how he sees the world, which is important 'cause that shapes how he acts.  It's all tied together, see?


The main guy, he's all about that pride, from the start. He wants a brother who can keep up with him, you know, someone to do all these cool things with. But Doodle, he's weak, he can't do any of that.  The main guy, he gets mad, even thinks about smotherin' the little kid. Can you believe that? But then Doodle smiles at him, and bam! All the anger melts away.  See, deep down, he loves his brother.

Ya know, the brain, it's a heck of a thing.  Folks used to say it was like a wax tablet, then a piece of paper, then a book. Now they say it's like a computer. But, lemme tell ya, those are just fancy words for somethin' complicated. 

See, information comes in through your senses - touch, sound, sight, all that jazz. Your brain takes that stuff and messes with it, like a recipe.  First, it breaks it down, little by little, like lookin' at a box.  Then, it puts it all back together, faster than you can say "jack rabbit."  It's like, if you see a box, your brain says, "Hey, that's a box!"  But it's not just seein' the box, it's knowin' it's a box, not a hole.

Now, your brain ain't just a sponge soakin' up everything. It's got a filter, like a bouncer at a club.  It says, "Hey, this is important, pay attention!" and "Nah, this ain't worth your time."  Like, you see a bunch of grass, but you don't notice each blade. But if your name gets called out in a crowd, boom, you hear it! 

The brain also got this memory thing goin' on. It stores stuff, like a big ol' warehouse.  It's got different rooms for different kinds of stuff - short-term, long-term, all that.  And it remembers by makin' connections, like a spider web.  So when you remember somethin', it's like followin' a thread through the web.

Alright, so this Huxley fella, he's givin' us the lowdown on how technology and big ol' corporations are gonna mess us all up someday. He writes this book, "Brave New World," and it's a real downer.  Everyone in this world is all about being part of the crowd and gettin' their instant gratification fix.  They don't care about bein' individuals, 'cause the big boss man, the World Controller, tells 'em what to think and do. 

Huxley's kinda like a Marxist, see? He sees how these rich folks are usin' this system to keep the rest of us dumb and happy, just workin' and spendin' all the time. He calls it "false consciousness."  It's like they're puttin' a blindfold on us so we don't see how the real world works.  We're all just pawns in their game, chasin' after the next shiny thing, and they're siphonin' off all the dough.

These folks in the book, they got these different classes, like the Deltas, Gammas, and all that.  They're all conditioned from birth to be happy with their lot in life,  even if it means they're bein' used.  They don't even know they're bein' used!

And the worst part is, the people at the top, the Alphas and Betas, they know what's goin' on, but they don't care. They just keep on enjoyin' their fancy lives, leavin' the rest of us to rot.

Huxley even shows how this system crushes real human connection. Nobody in this world has any real feelings, no deep thoughts, nothin'.  They're just talkin' about how good lookin' the chicks are or how many times they slept with 'em. It's all just surface stuff.  

It's like Huxley's sayin', if we keep lettin' technology and big corporations run our lives, we're gonna lose our humanity. We'll become nothin' more than robots, followin' orders and spendin' all our time on empty pleasures.

Been at this University Park place for a couple years now, almost three.  Gotta say, getting around this campus is a real pain in the neck. Back when I was livin' in  East Halls, which is like, way outta the way,  getting to classes down near Willard building felt like a cross-country trek. Sometimes, especially when the weather was crappier than a week-old burger, it took me a good 25 minutes just to walk there. Talked to an old-timer who graduated not too long ago, and he told me how they used to have all this empty space between East Halls and the rest of campus. Now, they've crammed in all these new buildings, sports fields, and apartments. With all the changes, it's getting harder and harder to get around.  What's the solution? Bikes, man!  

Had a buddy tell me the other day how he'd gotten back into ridin' bikes. Said it was the only way to get around, and he was glad he'd started again.  You know, bikes are good for ya, plus they're the fastest way to get from here to there. You can ride a bike with just some oatmeal in your belly and cover 30 miles without breaking a sweat. I live off campus now, just as far from the center of campus as some of those dorms.  Best thing I did this year was buy myself a bike.  

My classes are in Thomas building, which is a good 25-minute walk from my place. But on my bike? Five minutes, tops!  The only problem is  Pollock Road ain't always the safest route. It's a straight shot, but there are times when it's a real pain to ride.  Walkin' ain't bad, but I ain't got the time. If I didn't have my bike, I'd be walkin'  to Thomas every day, which would be a good 30-40 minutes each way. That's over two and a half hours a week just walkin' to class! Add to that all the other places I gotta go, and it'd be a real time suck.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm.
